\\section{3.1 DATA AND SIGNALS}

Figure 3.1 shows a scenario in which a scientist working in a research company, Sky Research, needs to order a book related to her research from an online bookseller, Scientific Books.

\\textbf{Figure 3.1} Communication at the physical layer

\\begin{center}
\\includegraphics[width=\\textwidth]{_page_0_Figure_5.jpeg}
\\end{center}

We can think of five different levels of communication between Alice, the computer on which our scientist is working, and Bob, the computer that provides online service. Communication at application, transport, network, or data-link is \\textit{logical}; communication at the physical layer is \\textit{physical}. For simplicity, we have shown only

\\documentclass{article}
\\usepackage{graphicx}
\\usepackage{color}
\\usepackage{amsmath}

\\begin{document}

host-to-router, router-to-router, and router-to-host, but the switches are also involved in the physical communication.

Although Alice and Bob need to exchange \\emph{data}, communication at the physical layer means exchanging \\emph{signals}. Data need to be transmitted and received, but the media have to change data to signals. Both data and the signals that represent them can be either \\textbf{analog} or \\textbf{digital} in form.

\\section{3.1.1 Analog and Digital Data}

Data can be analog or digital. The term \\textbf{analog data} refers to information that is continuous; \\textbf{digital data} refers to information that has discrete states. For example, an analog clock that has hour, minute, and second hands gives information in a continuous form; the movements of the hands are continuous. On the other hand, a digital clock that reports the hours and the minutes will change suddenly from 8:05 to 8:06.

Analog data, such as the sounds made by a human voice, take on continuous values. When someone speaks, an analog wave is created in the air. This can be captured by a microphone and converted to an analog signal or sampled and converted to a digital signal.

Digital data take on discrete values. For example, data are stored in computer memory in the form of 0s and 1s. They can be converted to a digital signal or modulated into an analog signal for transmission across a medium.

\\section{3.1.2 Analog and Digital Signals}

Like the data they represent, \\textbf{signals} can be either analog or digital. An \\textbf{analog signal} has infinitely many levels of intensity over a period of time. As the wave moves from value $A$ to value $B$, it passes through and includes an infinite number of values along its path. A \\textbf{digital signal}, on the other hand, can have only a limited number of defined values. Although each value can be any number, it is often as simple as 1 and 0.

The simplest way to show signals is by plotting them on a pair of perpendicular axes. The vertical axis represents the value or strength of a signal. The horizontal axis represents time. Figure~\\ref{fig:analog-digital} illustrates an analog signal and a digital signal. The curve representing the analog signal passes through an infinite number of points. The vertical lines of the digital signal, however, demonstrate the sudden jump that the signal makes from value to value.

\\begin{figure}[htbp]
\\centering
\\includegraphics[width=0.9\\textwidth]{_page_0_Figure_12.jpeg}
\\caption{Comparison of analog and digital signals}
\\label{fig:analog-digital}
\\end{figure}

\\end{document}

\\section{3.1.3 Periodic and Nonperiodic}
Both analog and digital signals can take one of two forms: \\textit{periodic} or \\textit{nonperiodic} (sometimes referred to as \\textit{aperiodic}; the prefix \\textit{a} in Greek means ``non'').
A \\textbf{periodic signal} completes a pattern within a measurable time frame, called a \\textbf{period}, and repeats that pattern over subsequent identical periods. The completion of one full pattern is called a \\textbf{cycle}. A \\textbf{nonperiodic signal} changes without exhibiting a pattern or cycle that repeats over time.
Both analog and digital signals can be periodic or nonperiodic. In data communications, we commonly use periodic analog signals and nonperiodic digital signals, as we will see in future chapters.
\\begin{center}
\\textbf{In data communications, we commonly use periodic analog signals and nonperiodic digital signals.}
\\end{center}
\\section{3.2 PERIODIC ANALOG SIGNALS}
Periodic analog signals can be classified as simple or composite. A simple periodic analog signal, a \\textbf{sine wave}, cannot be decomposed into simpler signals. A composite periodic analog signal is composed of multiple sine waves.
\\subsection{3.2.1 Sine Wave}
The sine wave is the most fundamental form of a periodic analog signal. When we visualize it as a simple oscillating curve, its change over the course of a cycle is smooth and consistent, a continuous, rolling flow. Figure 3.3 shows a sine wave. Each cycle consists of a single arc above the time axis followed by a single arc below it.
\\begin{center}
\\textbf{Figure 3.3} A sine wave
\\end{center}
\\begin{center}
\\includegraphics[width=0.8\\textwidth]{_page_0_Figure_12.jpeg}
\\end{center}
\\begin{center}
\\textbf{We discuss a mathematical approach to sine waves in Appendix E.}
\\end{center}
A sine wave can be represented by three parameters: the \\textit{peak amplitude}, the \\textit{frequency}, and the \\textit{phase}. These three parameters fully describe a sine wave.

\\section{Peak Amplitude}
The \\textbf{peak amplitude} of a signal is the absolute value of its highest intensity, proportional to the energy it carries. For electric signals, peak amplitude is normally measured in \\textit{volts}. Figure~3.4 shows two signals and their peak amplitudes.

\\begin{figure}[htbp]
\\centering
\\includegraphics[width=0.8\\textwidth]{_page_0_Figure_5.jpeg}
\\caption{Two signals with the same phase and frequency, but different amplitudes}
\\label{fig:3.4}
\\end{figure}

\\subsection*{Example 3.1}
The power in your house can be represented by a sine wave with a peak amplitude of 155 to 170 V. However, it is common knowledge that the voltage of the power in U.S. homes is 110 to 120 V. This discrepancy is due to the fact that these are root mean square (rms) values. The signal is squared and then the average amplitude is calculated. The peak value is equal to $2^{1/2} \\times \\text{rms}$ value.

\\subsection*{Example 3.2}
The voltage of a battery is a constant; this constant value can be considered a sine wave, as we will see later. For example, the peak value of an AA battery is normally 1.5 V.

\\section{Period and Frequency}
\\textbf{Period} refers to the amount of time, in seconds, a signal needs to complete 1 cycle. \\textbf{Frequency} refers to the number of periods in 1 s. Note that period and frequency are just one characteristic defined in two ways. Period is the inverse of frequency, and frequency is the inverse of period, as the following formulas show.
\\begin{equation}
f = \\frac{1}{T} \\quad \\text{and} \\quad T = \\frac{1}{f}
\\end{equation}

\\textbf{Frequency and period are the inverse of each other.}

Figure~3.5 shows two signals and their frequencies. Period is formally expressed in seconds. Frequency is formally expressed in \\textbf{Hertz} (\\textbf{Hz}), which is cycle per second. Units of period and frequency are shown in Table~3.1.

\\subsection*{Figure 3.5} Two signals with the same amplitude and phase, but different frequencies

\\begin{figure}[h]
\\centering
\\includegraphics[width=0.8\\textwidth]{_page_0_Figure_3.jpeg}
\\caption{Two signals with the same amplitude and phase, but different frequencies}
\\end{figure}

\\begin{table}[h]
\\centering
\\caption{Units of period and frequency}
\\begin{tabular}{|c|c|c|c|}
\\hline
\\textbf{Period} & & \\textbf{Frequency} & \\\\
\\hline
Unit & Equivalent & Unit & Equivalent \\\\
\\hline
Seconds (s) & $1\\ \\mathrm{s}$ & Hertz (Hz) & $1\\ \\mathrm{Hz}$ \\\\
