\\end{itemize}

\\subsection*{Example 12.1}
The stations on a wireless ALOHA network are a maximum of 600 km apart. If we assume that signals propagate at $3 \\times 10^8$ m/s, we find $T_p = (600 \\times 10^3) / (3 \\times 10^8) = 2$ ms. For $K = 2$, the range of $R$ is $\\{0, 1, 2, 3\\}$. This means that $T_B$ can be 0, 2, 4, or 6 ms, based on the outcome of the random variable $R$.

\\subsection*{Vulnerable time}
Let us find the \\textit{vulnerable time}, the length of time in which there is a possibility of collision. We assume that the stations send fixed-length frames with each frame taking $T_{fr}$ seconds to send. Figure 12.4 shows the vulnerable time for station B.

