\\caption{Digital signal created by four stations in CDMA}
\\label{fig:cdma_signal}
\\end{figure}

In the Walsh table, each row is a sequence of chips. $W_1$ for a one-chip sequence has one row and one column. We can choose $-1$ or $+1$ for the chip for this trivial table (we chose $+1$). According to Walsh, if we know the table for $N$ sequences $W_N$, we can create the table for $2N$ sequences $W_{2N}$, as shown in Figure~\\ref{fig:walsh_construction}. The $\\overline{W_N}$ with the overbar stands for the complement of $W_N$, where each $+1$ is changed to $-1$ and vice versa. Figure~\\ref{fig:walsh_construction} also shows how we can create $W_2$ and $W_4$ from $W_1$. After we select $W_1$, $W_2$ can be made from four $W_1$s, with the last one the complement of $W_1$. After $W_2$ is generated, $W_4$ can be made of four $W_2$s, with the last one the complement of $W_2$. Of course, $W_8$ is composed of four $W_4$s, and so on. Note that after $W_N$ is made, each station is assigned a chip corresponding to a row.

