\\includegraphics[width=0.8\\textwidth]{_page_0_Figure_3.jpeg}
\\end{center}
The user telephone or computer is connected to the \\textbf{signal points (SPs)}. The link between the telephone set and SP is common for the two networks. The signaling network uses nodes called \\textit{signal transport ports (STPs)} that receive and forward signaling messages. The signaling network also includes a \\textbf{service control point (SCP)} that controls the whole operation of the network. Other systems such as a database center may be included to provide stored information about the entire signaling network.

\\subsection{Signaling System Seven (SS7)}
The protocol that is used in the signaling network is called \\textit{Signaling System Seven (SS7)}. It is very similar to the five-layer Internet model we saw in Chapter 2, but the layers have different names, as shown in Figure 14.5.

