\\subsection{Data Frames}
Data frames are used for carrying data and control information.

\\subsection{Addressing Mechanism}
The IEEE 802.11 addressing mechanism specifies four cases, defined by the value of the two flags in the FC field, \\textit{To DS} and \\textit{From DS}. Each flag can be either 0 or 1, resulting in four different situations. The interpretation of the four addresses (address 1 to address 4) in the MAC frame depends on the value of these flags, as shown in Table~\\ref{tab:addresses}.

\\begin{table}[h]
\\centering
\\caption{Addresses}
\\begin{tabular}{|c|c|c|c|c|c|}
\\hline
To DS & From DS & Address 1 & Address 2 & Address 3 & Address 4 \\\\
\\hline
0 & 0 & Destination & Source & BSS ID & N/A \\\\
\\hline
0 & 1 & Destination & Sending AP & Source & N/A \\\\
\\hline
1 & 0 & Receiving AP & Source & Destination & N/A \\\\
\\hline
1 & 1 & Receiving AP & Sending AP & Destination & Source \\\\
\\hline
\\end{tabular}
\\label{tab:addresses}
\\end{table}

Note that address 1 is always the address of the next device that the frame will visit. Address 2 is always the address of the previous device that the frame has left. Address 3 is the address of the final destination station if it is not defined by address 1 or the original source station if it is not defined by address 2. Address 4 is the original source when the distribution system is also wireless.

\\begin{itemize}
    \\item \\textbf{Case 1: 00} In this case, $To\\ DS = 0$ and $From\\ DS = 0$. This means that the frame is not going to a distribution system ($To\\ DS = 0$) and is not coming from a distribution system ($From\\ DS = 0$). The frame is going from one station in a BSS to another without passing through the distribution system. The addresses are shown in Figure~\\ref{fig:addr1}.
    \\item \\textbf{Case 2: 01} In this case, $To\\ DS = 0$ and $From\\ DS = 1$. This means that the frame is coming from a distribution system ($From\\ DS = 1$). The frame is coming from an
