\\subsection*{IEEE 802.11 Infrared}

IEEE 802.11 infrared uses infrared light in the range of 800 to 950 nm. The modulation technique is called \\textit{pulse position modulation (PPM)}. For a 1-Mbps data rate, a 4-bit sequence is first mapped into a 16-bit sequence in which only one bit is set to 1 and the rest are set to 0. For a 2-Mbps data rate, a 2-bit sequence is first mapped into a 4-bit sequence in which only one bit is set to 1 and the rest are set to 0. The mapped sequences are then converted to optical signals; the presence of light specifies 1, the absence of light specifies 0. See Figure 15.15.

