\\subsection{Figure 19.10 Use of ICMPv4 in traceroute}

\\begin{figure}[h]
\\centering
\\includegraphics[width=0.8\\textwidth]{_page_0_Figure_3.jpeg}
\\caption{Use of ICMPv4 in traceroute}
\\end{figure}

The \\textit{traceroute} program also sets a timer to find the round-trip time for each router and the destination. Most \\textit{traceroute} programs send three messages to each device, with the same TTL value, to be able to find a better estimate for the round-trip time. The following shows an example of a \\textit{traceroute} program, which uses three probes for each device and gets three RTTs.

\\begin{verbatim}
$ traceroute printers.com
traceroute to printers.com (13.1.69.93), 30 hops max, 38-byte packets
1 route.front.edu (153.18.31.254) 0.622 ms 0.891 ms 0.875 ms
2 ceneric.net (137.164.32.140) 3.069 ms 2.875 ms 2.930 ms
3 satire.net (132.16.132.20) 3.071 ms 2.876 ms 2.929 ms
4 alpha.printers.com (13.1.69.93) 5.922 ms 5.048 ms 4.922 ms
\\end{verbatim}

\\subsection{Tracert}

The \\textit{tracert} program in windows behaves differently. The \\textit{tracert} messages are encapsulated directly in IP datagrams. The \\textit{tracert}, like \\textit{traceroute}, sends echo-request messages. However, when the last echo request reaches the destination host, an echo-reply message is issued.

\\subsection{19.2.3 ICMP Checksum}

In ICMP the checksum is calculated over the entire message (header and data).

\\subsection{Example 19.12}

Figure 19.11 shows an example of checksum calculation for a simple echo-request message. We randomly chose the identifier to be 1 and the sequence number to be 9. The message is divided

