\\begin{document}

interface except the one from which the packet arrived. This guarantees that flooding stops somewhere in the network (where a node has only one interface). We need to convince ourselves that, after receiving all new LSPs, each node creates the comprehensive LSDB as shown in Figure~\\ref{fig:lsps}. This LSDB is the same for each node and shows the whole map of the internet. In other words, a node can make the whole map if it needs to, using this LSDB.

\\begin{figure}[h]
\\centering
\\includegraphics[width=0.8\\textwidth]{_page_0_Figure_3.jpeg}
\\caption{LSPs created and sent out by each node to build LSDB}
\\label{fig:lsps}
\\end{figure}

We can compare the link-state routing algorithm with the distance-vector routing algorithm. In the distance-vector routing algorithm, each router tells its neighbors what it knows about the whole internet; in the link-state routing algorithm, each router tells the whole internet what it knows about its neighbors.

\\subsection{Formation of Least-Cost Trees}

To create a least-cost tree for itself, using the shared LSDB, each node needs to run the famous \\textbf{Dijkstra Algorithm}. This iterative algorithm uses the following steps:

\\begin{enumerate}
    \\item The node chooses itself as the root of the tree, creating a tree with a single node, and sets the total cost of each node based on the information in the LSDB.
    \\item The node selects one node, among all nodes not in the tree, which is closest to the root, and adds this to the tree. After this node is added to the tree, the cost of all other nodes not in the tree needs to be updated because the paths may have been changed.
    \\item The node repeats step 2 until all nodes are added to the tree.
\\end{enumerate}

We need to convince ourselves that the above three steps finally create the least-cost tree. Table~\\ref{tab:dijkstra} shows a simplified version of Dijkstra's algorithm.

\\begin{table}[h]
\\centering
\\caption{Dijkstra's Algorithm}
\\begin{tabular}{|l|l|}
\\hline
