\\subsection{22.1.4 Autoconfiguration}

One of the interesting features of IPv6 addressing is the \\textbf{autoconfiguration} of hosts. As we discussed in IPv4, the host and routers are originally configured manually by the network manager. However, the Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol, DHCP, can be used to allocate an IPv4 address to a host that joins the network. In IPv6, DHCP protocol can still be used to allocate an IPv6 address to a host, but a host can also configure itself.

When a host in IPv6 joins a network, it can configure itself using the following process:

\\begin{enumerate}
    \\item The host first creates a \\textbf{link local address} for itself. This is done by taking the 10-bit link local prefix (1111 1110 10), adding 54 zeros, and adding the 64-bit interface identifier, which any host knows how to generate from its interface card. The result is a 128-bit link local address.
    \\item The host then tests to see if this link local address is unique and not used by other hosts. Since the 64-bit interface identifier is supposed to be unique, the link local
\\end{enumerate}

\\subsection{22.2 THE IPv6 PROTOCOL}
The change of the IPv6 address size requires the change in the IPv4 packet format. The designer of IPv6 decided to implement remedies for other shortcomings now that a change is inevitable. The following shows other changes implemented in the protocol in addition to changing address size and format.
\\begin{itemize}
    \\item \\textbf{Better header format.} IPv6 uses a new header format in which options are separated from the base header and inserted, when needed, between the base header and the data. This simplifies and speeds up the routing process because most of the options do not need to be checked by routers.
    \\item \\textbf{New options.} IPv6 has new options to allow for additional functionalities.
    \\item \\textbf{Allowance for extension.} IPv6 is designed to allow the extension of the protocol if required by new technologies or applications.
    \\item \\textbf{Support for resource allocation.} In IPv6, the type-of-service field has been removed, but two new fields, traffic class and flow label, have been added to enable the source to request special handling of the packet. This mechanism can be used to support traffic such as real-time audio and video.
    \\item \\textbf{Support for more security.} The encryption and authentication options in IPv6 provide confidentiality and integrity of the packet.
\\end{itemize}

\\subsubsection{22.2.1 Packet Format}
The IPv6 packet is shown in Figure 22.6. Each packet is composed of a base header followed by the payload. The base header occupies 40 bytes, whereas payload can be up to 65,535 bytes of information. The description of fields follows.

\\begin{figure}[h]
    \\centering
    \\includegraphics[width=0.8\\textwidth]{_page_0_Figure_12.jpeg}
    \\caption{IPv6 datagram}
    \\label{fig:ipv6_datagram}
\\end{figure}

\\begin{itemize}
    \\item \\textbf{Version.} The 4-bit version field defines the version number of the IP. For IPv6, the value is 6.
    \\item \\textbf{Traffic class.} The 8-bit traffic class field is used to distinguish different payloads with different delivery requirements. It replaces the \\textit{type-of-service} field in IPv4.
    \\item \\textbf{Flow label.} The flow label is a 20-bit field that is designed to provide special handling for a particular flow of data. We will discuss this field later.
    \\item \\textbf{Payload length.} The 2-byte payload length field defines the length of the IP datagram excluding the header. Note that IPv4 defines two fields related to the length: header length and total length. In IPv6, the length of the base header is fixed (40 bytes); only the length of the payload needs to be defined.
    \\item \\textbf{Next header.} The \\textbf{next header} is an 8-bit field defining the type of the first extension header (if present) or the type of the data that follows the base header in the datagram. This field is similar to the protocol field in IPv4, but we talk more about it when we discuss the payload.
    \\item \\textbf{Hop limit.} The 8-bit hop limit field serves the same purpose as the TTL field in IPv4.
    \\item \\textbf{Source and destination addresses.} The source address field is a 16-byte (128-bit) Internet address that identifies the original source of the datagram. The destination address field is a 16-byte (128-bit) Internet address that identifies the destination of the datagram.
    \\item \\textbf{Payload.} Compared to IPv4, the payload field in IPv6 has a different format and meaning, as shown in Figure~\\ref{fig:ipv6_payload}.
\\end{itemize}

\\begin{figure}[htbp]
    \\centering
    \\includegraphics[width=0.8\\textwidth]{_page_0_Figure_11.jpeg}
    \\caption{Payload in an IPv6 datagram}
    \\label{fig:ipv6_payload}
\\end{figure}

The payload in IPv6 means a combination of zero or more extension headers (options) followed by the data from other protocols (UDP, TCP, and so on). In IPv6, options, which are part of the header in IPv4, are designed as extension headers. The payload can have as many extension headers as required by the situation. Each extension header has two mandatory fields, next header and the length.

\\subsection{Extension Header}
An IPv6 packet is made of a base header and some extension headers. The length of the base header is fixed at 40 bytes. However, to give more functionality to the IP datagram, the base header can be followed by up to six \\textbf{extension headers}. Many of these headers are options in IPv4. Six types of extension headers have been defined. These are hop-by-hop option, source routing, fragmentation, authentication, encrypted security payload, and destination option (see Figure~\\ref{fig:ext_headers}).

\\begin{figure}[htbp]
\\centering
\\includegraphics[width=0.8\\textwidth]{_page_0_Figure_5.jpeg}
\\caption{Extension header types}
\\label{fig:ext_headers}
\\end{figure}

We briefly describe the extension headers in this section, but the complete description is posted at the book website.

\\textbf{Complete descriptions of extension headers are posted on the book website under Extra Materials for Chapter 22.}

\\subsubsection{Hop-by-Hop Option}
The \\textit{hop-by-hop option} is used when the source needs to pass information to all routers visited by the datagram. For example, perhaps routers must be informed about certain management, debugging, or control functions. Or, if the length of the datagram is more than the usual 65,535 bytes, routers must have this information. So far, only three hop-by-hop options have been defined: Pad1, PadN, and jumbo payload.

\\begin{itemize}
    \\item \\textit{Pad1.} This option is 1 byte long and is designed for alignment purposes. Some options need to start at a specific bit of the 32-bit word. If an option falls short of this requirement by exactly one byte, Pad1 is added.
    \\item \\textit{PadN.} PadN is similar in concept to Pad1. The difference is that PadN is used when 2 or more bytes are needed for alignment.
    \\item \\textit{Jumbo payload.} Recall that the length of the payload in the IP datagram can be a maximum of 65,535 bytes. However, if for any reason a longer payload is required, we can use the jumbo payload option to define this longer length.
\\end{itemize}

\\subsubsection{Destination Option}
The \\textbf{destination option} is used when the source needs to pass information to the destination only. Intermediate routers are not permitted access to this information. The format of the destination option is the same as the hop-by-hop option. So far, only the Pad1 and PadN options have been defined.

\\subsection{22.3 THE ICMPv6 PROTOCOL}
Another protocol that has been modified in version 6 of the TCP/IP protocol suite is ICMP. This new version, Internet Control Message Protocol version 6 (ICMPv6), follows the same strategy and purposes of version 4. ICMPv6, however, is more complicated than ICMPv4: some protocols that were independent in version 4 are now part of ICMPv6 and some new messages have been added to make it more useful. Figure~\\ref{fig:icmpv4v6} compares the network layer of version 4 to that of version 6. The ICMP, ARP (discussed in Chapter~9), and IGMP protocols in version 4 (Chapter~21) are combined into one single protocol, ICMPv6.

\\begin{figure}[htbp]
\\centering
\\includegraphics[width=0.8\\textwidth]{_page_0_Picture_5.jpeg}
\\caption{Comparison of network layer in version 4 and version 6}
\\label{fig:icmpv4v6}
\\end{figure}

We briefly describe the ICMPv6 in this section, but the complete description is posted at the book website.

Complete descriptions of ICMPv6 messages are posted on the book website under Extra Materials for Chapter~22.

We can divide the messages in ICMPv6 into four groups: error-reporting messages, informational messages, neighbor-discovery messages, and group-membership messages, as shown in Figure~\\ref{fig:icmpv6categories}.

\\begin{figure}[htbp]
