\\section{24.1 INTRODUCTION}
After discussing the general principle behind the transport layer in the previous chapter, we concentrate on the transport protocols in the Internet in this chapter. Figure~\\ref{fig:24.1} shows the position of these three protocols in the TCP/IP protocol suite.

\\begin{figure}[htbp]
\\centering
\\includegraphics[width=\\textwidth]{_page_0_Figure_5.jpeg}
\\caption{Position of transport-layer protocols in the TCP/IP protocol suite}
\\label{fig:24.1}
\\end{figure}

\\subsection{24.1.1 Services}
Each protocol provides a different type of service and should be used appropriately.

\\textbf{UDP}
UDP is an unreliable connectionless transport-layer protocol used for its simplicity and efficiency in applications where error control can be provided by the application-layer process.

\\textbf{TCP}
TCP is a reliable connection-oriented protocol that can be used in any application where reliability is important.

\\textbf{SCTP}
SCTP is a new transport-layer protocol that combines the features of UDP and TCP.

\\subsection{24.1.2 Port Numbers}
As discussed in the previous chapter, a transport-layer protocol usually has several responsibilities. One is to create a process-to-process communication; these protocols use port numbers to accomplish this. Port numbers provide end-to-end addresses at the transport layer and allow multiplexing and demultiplexing at this layer, just as IP addresses do at the network layer. Table~\\ref{tab:24.1} gives some common port numbers for all three protocols we discuss in this chapter.

