The sending queue holds chunks 23 to 40. The chunks 23 to 36 have already been sent, but not acknowledged; they are outstanding chunks. The \\textit{curTSN} points to the next chunk to be sent (37). We assume that each chunk is 100 bytes, which means that 1400 bytes of data (chunks 23 to 36) are in transit. The sender at this moment has a retransmission queue. When a packet is sent, a retransmission timer starts for that packet. Some implementations use a single timer for the entire association, but we continue with our tradition of one timer for each packet for simplification. When the retransmission timer for a packet expires, or three SACKs arrive that declare a packet as missing (fast retransmission was discussed for TCP), the chunks in that packet are

moved to the retransmission queue to be resent. These chunks are considered lost, rather than outstanding. The chunks in the retransmission queue have priority. In other words, the next time the sender sends a chunk, it would be chunk 21 from the retransmission queue.

