\\subsection{TCP Client Design}
Figure~\\ref{fig:tcp-client-design} shows the design of objects and their relationship in the client program we are going to write. Before we explain this design, we need to mention that this applies only to our client program, which is very simple; it does not represent a design for standard applications, such as HTTP, which can be more complex.

The design shows that we have a socket object (of type \\texttt{Socket}) created by the client program to provide a connection between the client and the transport layer (TCP). We need one byte stream to send bytes to the socket. We also need one byte stream to receive bytes from the socket. In Java these two streams can be created using the two methods \\texttt{getOutputStream} and \\texttt{getInputStream}, provided in the \\texttt{Socket} class (Table~\\ref{tab:socket-methods}). In our program we need also two arrays of bytes, called \\texttt{sendBuff} and \\texttt{recvBuff}, to store bytes before sending them into the \\texttt{sendStream} and to store bytes after receiving them from the \\texttt{recvStream}. For simplicity, our program assumes that we have a method that makes the request as a string of characters, and a method that uses the response as a string of characters. In this design, we need to convert the request from the string to an array of bytes and change the array of bytes to the response. However, in other designs, we may use other strategies.

