\\subsection{Architecture}

To explain the architecture of e-mail, we give a common scenario, as shown in Figure~\\ref{fig:common_scenario}. Another possibility is the case in which Alice or Bob is directly connected to the corresponding mail server, in which LAN or WAN connection is not required, but this variation in the scenario does not affect our discussion.

\\begin{figure}[htbp]
\\centering
\\includegraphics[width=0.8\\textwidth]{_page_0_Figure_6.jpeg}
\\caption{Common scenario}
\\label{fig:common_scenario}
\\end{figure}

In the common scenario, the sender and the receiver of the e-mail, Alice and Bob respectively, are connected via a LAN or a WAN to two mail servers. The administrator has created one mailbox for each user where the received messages are stored. A \\emph{mail-box} is part of a server hard drive, a special file with permission restrictions. Only the owner of the mailbox has access to it. The administrator has also created a queue (spool) to store messages waiting to be sent.

A simple e-mail from Alice to Bob takes nine different steps, as shown in the figure. Alice and Bob use three different \\emph{agents}: a \\emph{user agent} (UA), a \\emph{message transfer agent} (MTA), and a \\emph{message access agent} (MAA). When Alice needs to send a message to

