\\subsection{29.5 BITTORRENT}
BitTorrent is a P2P protocol, designed by Bram Cohen, for sharing a large file among a set of peers. However, the term \\emph{sharing} in this context is different from other file-sharing protocols. Instead of one peer allowing another peer to download the whole file, a group of peers takes part in the process to give all peers in the group a copy of the file. File sharing is done in a collaborating process called a \\emph{torrent}. Each peer participating in a torrent downloads chunks of the large file from another peer that has it and uploads chunks of that file to other peers that do not have it, a kind of \\emph{tit-for-tat}, a trading game played by kids. The set of all peers that takes part in a torrent is referred to as a \\emph{swarm}. A peer in a swarm that has the complete content file is called a \\emph{seed}; a peer that has only part of the file and wants to download the rest is called a \\emph{leech}. In other words, a swarm is a combination of seeds and leeches. BitTorrent has gone through several versions and implementations. We first describe the original one, which uses a central node called a \\emph{tracker}. We then show how some new versions eliminate the tracker by using DHT.

\\subsection{29.5.1 BitTorrent with a Tracker}
In the original BitTorrent, there is another entity in a torrent, called the tracker, which, as the name implies, tracks the operation of the swarm, as described later. Figure~\\ref{fig:torrent} shows an example of a torrent with seeds, leeches, and the tracker.

