\\node[draw, rectangle, minimum width=2cm, minimum height=1cm, align=center] (ticket101) at (4,25.25) {\\textbf{Alice, Bob,} \\textbf{K$_\\text{S}$}};

\\node[draw, rectangle, minimum width=2cm, minimum height=1cm, align=center] (ticket102) at (4,25.5) {\\textbf{Alice, Bob,} \\textbf{K$_\\text{S}$}};

\\node[draw, rectangle, minimum width=2cm, minimum height=1cm, align=center] (ticket103) at (4,25.75) {\\textbf{Alice, Bob,} \\textbf{K$_\\text{S}$}};

\\node[draw, rectangle, minimum width=2cm, minimum height=1cm, align=center] (ticket104) at (4,26) {\\textbf{Alice, Bob,} \\textbf{K$_\\text{S}$}};

\\node[draw, rectangle, minimum width=2cm, minimum height=1cm, align=center] (ticket105) at (4,26.25) {\\textbf{Alice, Bob,} \\textbf{K$_\\text{S}$}};

\\node[draw, rectangle, minimum width=2cm, minimum height=1cm, align=center] (ticket106) at (4,26.5) {\\textbf{Alice, Bob,} \\textbf{K$_\\text{S}$}};

\\node[draw, rectangle, minimum width=2cm, minimum height=1cm, align=center] (ticket107) at (4,26.75) {\\textbf{Alice, Bob,} \\textbf{K$_\\text{S}$}};

\\node[draw, rectangle, minimum width=2cm

In the same way, Alice is also authenticated to Bob, because Bob trusts the KDC and the KDC has sent Bob the ticket that includes the identity of Alice.

\\subsection*{Symmetric-Key Agreement}

Alice and Bob can create a session key between themselves without using a KDC. This method of session-key creation is referred to as the \\emph{symmetric-key agreement}. Although there are several ways to accomplish this, we discuss only one method, Diffie-Hellman, which shows the basic idea used in more sophisticated (less prone to attack) methods.

\\subsection*{Diffie-Hellman Key Agreement}

In the \\emph{Diffie-Hellman protocol} two parties create a symmetric session key without the need of a KDC. Before establishing a symmetric key, the two parties need to choose two numbers $p$ and $g$. These two numbers have some properties discussed in number theory, but that discussion is beyond the scope of this book. These two numbers do not need to be confidential. They can be sent through the Internet; they can be public. Figure~\\ref{fig:diffie-hellman} shows the procedure.

\\begin{figure}[htbp]
\\centering
\\includegraphics[width=0.8\\textwidth]{_page_0_Figure_8.jpeg}
\\caption{Diffie-Hellman method}
\\label{fig:diffie-hellman}
\\end{figure}

The steps are as follows:

\\begin{enumerate}
\\item Alice chooses a large random number $x$ such that $0 \\le x \\le p-1$ and calculates $R_1 = g^x \\bmod p$. Bob chooses another large random number $y$ such that $0 \\le y \\le p-1$ and calculates $R_2 = g^y \\bmod p$.
\\item Alice sends $R_1$ to Bob. Note that Alice does not send the value of $x$; she sends only $R_1$.
\\item Bob sends $R_2$ to Alice. Again, note that Bob does not send the value of $y$, he sends only $R_2$.
\\item Alice calculates $K = (R_2)^x \\bmod p$. Bob also calculates $K = (R_1)^y \\bmod p$.
\\end{enumerate}

$K$ is the symmetric key for the session.

\\[
K = (g^x \\bmod p)^y \\bmod p = (g^y \\bmod p)^x \\bmod p = g^{xy} \\bmod p
\\]

\\subsection{Certification Authority}
The common approach to distributing public keys is to create \\textbf{public-key certificates}. Bob wants two things; he wants people to know his public key, and he wants no one to accept a forged public key as his. Bob can go to a \\textbf{certification authority (CA)}, a federal or state organization that binds a public key to an entity and issues a certificate. Figure~\\ref{fig:ca} shows the concept.

\\begin{figure}[htbp]
\\centering
\\includegraphics[width=0.8\\textwidth]{_page_0_Picture_5.jpeg}
\\caption{Certification authority}
\\label{fig:ca}
\\end{figure}

The CA itself has a well-known public key that cannot be forged. The CA checks Bob's identification (using a picture ID along with other proof). It then asks for Bob's public key and writes it on the certificate. To prevent the certificate itself from being forged, the CA signs the certificate with its private key. Now Bob can upload the signed certificate. Anyone who wants Bob's public key downloads the signed certificate and uses the authority's public key to extract Bob's public key.

\\subsection{X.509}
Although the use of a CA has solved the problem of public-key fraud, it has created a side effect. Each certificate may have a different format. If Alice wants to use a program to automatically download different certificates and digests belonging to different people, the program may not be able to do this. One certificate may have the public key in one format and another certificate may have it in a different format. The public key may be on the first line in one certificate and on the third line in another. Anything that needs to be used universally must have a universal format. To remove this side effect, the ITU has designed \\textbf{X.509}, a recommendation that has been accepted by the Internet with some changes. X.509 is a structured way to describe the certificate. It uses a

