\\subsection{Cryptographic Message Syntax (CMS)}
To define how security services, such as confidentiality or integrity, can be added to MIME content types, S/MIME has defined \\textbf{Cryptographic Message Syntax (CMS)}. The syntax in each case defines the exact encoding scheme for each content type. The following describe the types of messages and different subtypes that are created from these messages. For details, the reader is referred to RFC 3369 and RFC 3370.

\\subsubsection{Data Content Type}
This is an arbitrary string. The object created is called \\textit{Data}.

\\subsubsection{Signed-Data Content Type}
This type provides only integrity of data. It contains any data type plus zero or more signature values. The encoded result is an \\textit{object} called \\textit{signedData}. Figure~\\ref{fig:signed-data} shows the process of creating an object of this type. The following are the steps in the process:
\\begin{enumerate}
    \\item For each signer, a message digest is created from the content using the specific hash algorithm chosen by that signer.
    \\item Each message digest is signed with the private key of the signer.
    \\item The content, signature values, certificates, and algorithms are then collected to create the \\textit{signedData} object.
\\end{enumerate}

\\begin{figure}[htbp]
    \\centering
    \\includegraphics[width=\\textwidth]{_page_0_Figure_12.jpeg}
    \\caption{Signed-data content type}
    \\label{fig:signed-data}
\\end{figure}

Note that, in this case, the content is not necessarily a personal message. It can be a document whose integrity needs to be preserved. The sender can collect the signatures and then send (or store) them with the message.

\\subsubsection{Enveloped-Data Content Type}
This type is used to provide privacy for the message. It contains any message type plus zero or more encrypted keys and certificates. The encoded result is an \\textit{object} called \\textit{envelopedData}. Figure~\\ref{fig:enveloped-data} shows the process of creating an object of this type.

\\subsection{Enveloped-data content type}
\\begin{figure}[h]
\\centering
\\includegraphics[width=0.8\\textwidth]{_page_0_Figure_3.jpeg}
\\caption{Enveloped-data content type}
\\label{fig:enveloped-data}
\\end{figure}

\\begin{enumerate}
    \\item A pseudorandom session key is created for the symmetric-key algorithms to be used.
    \\item For each recipient, a copy of the session key is encrypted with the public key of that recipient.
    \\item The content is encrypted using the defined algorithm and created session key.
    \\item The encrypted contents, encrypted session keys, algorithm used, and certificates are encoded using Radix-64.
\\end{enumerate}

Note that, in this case, we can have one or more recipients.

\\subsection{Digested-Data Content Type}
This type is used to provide integrity for the message. The result is normally used as the content for the enveloped-data content type. The encoded result is an \\textit{object} called \\textit{digestedData}. Figure~\\ref{fig:digest} shows the process of creating an object of this type.

\\begin{figure}[h]
\\centering
\\includegraphics[width=0.8\\textwidth]{_page_0_Figure_12.jpeg}
\\caption{Digested-data content type}
\\label{fig:digest}
\\end{figure}

\\begin{enumerate}
    \\item A message digest is calculated from the content.
\\end{enumerate}

\\subsection{Encrypted-Data Content Type}
This type is used to create an encrypted version of any content type. Although this looks like the enveloped-data content type, the encrypted-data content type has no recipient. It can be used to store the encrypted data instead of transmitting it. The process is very simple: the user employs any key (normally derived from the password) and any algorithm to encrypt the content. The encrypted content is stored without including the key or the algorithm. The object created is called \\textit{encryptedData}.

\\subsection{Authenticated-Data Content Type}
This type is used to provide authentication of the data. The object is called \\textit{authenticatedData}. Figure~\\ref{fig:auth-data} shows the process.

\\begin{figure}[htbp]
\\centering
\\includegraphics[width=0.8\\textwidth]{_page_0_Figure_8.jpeg}
\\caption{Authenticated-data content type}
\\label{fig:auth-data}
\\end{figure}

\\begin{enumerate}
    \\item Using a pseudorandom generator, a MAC key is generated for each recipient.
    \\item The MAC key is encrypted with the public key of the recipient.
    \\item A MAC is created for the content.
    \\item The content, MAC, algorithms, and other information are collected to form the authenticatedData object.
\\end{enumerate}

\\subsection{Key Management}
The key management in S/MIME is a combination of key management used by X.509 and PGP. S/MIME uses public-key certificates signed by the certificate authorities defined by X.509. However, the user is responsible for maintaining the web of trust to verify signatures as defined by PGP.

\\subsection{Cryptographic Algorithms}
S/MIME defines several cryptographic algorithms. We leave the details of these algorithms to the books dedicated to security in the Internet.

\\subsubsection{Example 32.1}
